\\section\{Implementation of the option pricing models\}\
\
The fundamental theorem of finance states that in an arbitrage-free model with a single factor, the price of the financial asset obeys the following valuation equation:\
\
\\begin\{equation\}\
\\frac\{1\}\{2\} \\sigma^2(t, x) \\frac\{\\partial^2 P(t, x)\}\{\\partial x^2\} + [\\mu(t, x) - \\lambda(t, x)\\sigma(t, x)]\\frac\{\\partial P(t, x)\}\{\\partial x\} + \\frac\{\\partial P(t, x)\}\{\\partial t\} - r(t, x)P(t, x) + b(t, x) = 0\
\\end\{equation\}\
\
where:\
\
\\begin\{itemize\}\
    \\item The first term, $\\frac\{1\}\{2\} \\sigma^2(t, x) \\frac\{\\partial^2 P\}\{\\partial x^2\}$, reflects the diffusion or variance in the price of the underlying asset, accounting for the uncertainty or risk.\
\
    \\item The second term, $\\mu(t, x) - \\lambda(t, x) \\sigma(t, x)$, adjusts the expected return by the market price of risk times volatility, which brings the drift term in line with an arbitrage-free market.\
\
    \\item The third term, $\\frac\{\\partial P\}\{\\partial t\}$, denotes the sensitivity of the option's price to the passage of time, also known as theta in options Greeks.\
\
    \\item The fourth term, $-r(t, x) P(t, x)$, subtracts the risk-free growth of the option's price.\
\
    \\item The last term, $+b(t, x)$, adds the cost of carry benefits into the equation.\
\\end\{itemize\}\
\
Setting the sum of these terms to zero ensures that the derivative is correctly priced to prevent arbitrage. This PDE forms the basis of many derivative pricing models, allowing for the valuation of options and other financial instruments under a variety of conditions.\
\
One of the underlying principles is the arbitrage-free market model. The equation is based on the assumption of an arbitrage-free market with one factor, meaning that there is no possibility to make a risk-free profit through trading strategies, and the model is dependent on a single source of market risk or uncertainty \\cite\{hull2017\}. These are foundational assumptions required for the model to hold \\cite\{hull2017\}. These typically include assumptions such as the frictionless market, no arbitrage opportunities, a constant risk-free rate, the ability to borrow and lend at the risk-free rate, and the possibility to buy and sell any amount of an asset. The price of the financial asset can be expressed in terms of $P(t, x)$ as the price of the derivative at time $t$ given the current state of the underlying asset $x$.\
\
\\begin\{itemize\}\
     \\item \{$\\sigma(t, x)$:\} This represents the volatility of the underlying asset. It is a measure of how much the asset's price is expected to fluctuate over time.\
\
     \\item \{$\\mu(t, x)$:\} This is the expected return or drift rate of the underlying asset.\
\
    \\item \{$\\lambda(t, x)$:\} This is the market price of risk. It accounts for the premium investors demand for taking on risk.\
\
    \\item \{$r(t, x)$:\} The theoretically constant rate of return on a risk-free investment. In practice, this is often approximated using government securities.\
\
    \\item \{$b(t, x)$:\} This term includes the cost of carry, which could be dividends paid out or convenience yield.\
\\end\{itemize\}\
\
\
The solution to this PDE, under appropriate boundary conditions (which depend on the type of financial derivative being modeled), gives us the fair price of the derivative in question. The Black-Scholes equation, specifically, provides solutions for European call and put options, but the methodology can be extended to a wide range of financial derivatives.\
\
